<section xml:id="section-strategies-for-graphing-lines">
  <title>Strategies for Graphing Lines</title>
  <objectives>
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-plot-graph-from-slope-intercept-form" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>

      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-plot-graph-from-point-slope-form" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>

      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-plot-graph-from-standard-form" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>

      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-plot-vertical-or-horizontal-line" text="local">MTH 60 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Previous several sections covered methods for plotting a graph of a linear equation in two
      variables.
    </p>
    <p>
      We've learned three forms for a linear equation:      
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="31% 31% 31%" margins="0%">
      <p>
        slope-intercept form <m>y=mx+b</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        point-slope form <m>y=m\left(x-x_0\right)+y_0</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        standard form <m>Ax+By=C</m>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      We've studied two special types of line:
    </p>
    <sidebyside>
      <p>
        horizontal line <m>y=k</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        vertical line <m>x=h</m>
      </p>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      We've practiced three ways to graph a line:
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="31% 31% 31%" margins="0%">
      <p>
        building a table of <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values
      </p>
      <p>
        plotting <em>one</em> point (often the <m>y</m>-intercept) and drawing slope triangles
      </p>
      <p>
        plotting its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept
      </p>
    </sidebyside>

    <p>
      In this section, we review these ideas, especially what steps to take to plot a graph of a              <idx><h>Graphing</h><h>linear equations in two variables</h></idx>
      linear equation.                                                                                        <idx><h>Linear equations in two variables</h><h>graphing</h></idx>
    </p>

    <figure>
      <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
      <video youtubeplaylist="PLmuZCPhWPt-dSIb9W3SsQGsoWCmjMihcY" />
    </figure>

  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>Graphing Lines in Slope-Intercept Form</title>
    <p>
      To review various methods for plotting a line, we'll start by taking one line, <m>y=-2x+1</m>,
      and graph it using each of the strategies we've learned.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Building a Table</title>
      <p>
        First, we'll graph <m>y=-2x+1</m> by building a table of values. Our first task is to pick
        some <m>x</m>-values to use in the table, and we arbitrarily choose <m>-2,-1,0,1,2</m>. It's
        a good habit to use at least five values when plotting this way. After this, we carefully
        evaluate <m>y</m> over and over, and plot the resulting points.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="50% 44%" margins="0%">
        <figure>
          <caption>Table for <m>y=-2x+1</m></caption>
          <tabular valign="top">
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell><m>x</m>-value</cell>
              <cell halign="center"><m>y</m>-value</cell>
              <cell>Point</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\highlight{-2}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\begin{aligned}[t]y\amp=-2(\substitute{-2})+1\\\amp=5\end{aligned}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(-2,5)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\highlight{-1}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\begin{aligned}[t]y\amp=-2(\substitute{-1})+1\\\amp=3\end{aligned}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(-1,3)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\highlight{0}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\begin{aligned}[t]y\amp=-2(\substitute{0})+1\\\amp=1\end{aligned}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(0,1)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\highlight{1}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\begin{aligned}[t]y\amp=-2(\substitute{1})+1\\\amp=-1\end{aligned}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(1,-1)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>\highlight{2}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>\begin{aligned}[t]y\amp=-2(\substitute{2})+1\\\amp=-3\end{aligned}</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(2,-3)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <caption>Graphing <m>y=-2x+1</m> using a table of values</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              this is a graph of the line y=-2x+1. The following points on the line are plotted:
              (-2,5),(-1,3),(0,1),(1,-1),(2,-3)
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="summary-graph-using-table">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-3,
                    xmax=3,
                    ymin=-6,
                    ymax=6,
                    width=0.44\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = -2.5:3]{-2*x+1} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {$y=-2x+1$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2, 5) (-1, 3) (0, 1) (1, -1) (2, -3)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Using Slope Triangles</title>
      <p>
        Although making a table is straightforward, the slope triangle method is faster and
        reinforces the true meaning of slope. With the slope triangle method, we first identify some
        point on the line. Our line is in
        <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>, so we
        know the <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,1)</m>. Plot this first, and then we can draw slope
        triangles in both directions to find more points. The slope we will use is also apparent:
        <m>-2=\frac{-2}{1}</m>.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <figure>
          <caption>Marking a point and some slope triangles</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="summary-slope-intercept">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-3,
                    xmax=3,
                    ymin=-6,
                    ymax=6,
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 1)} node[below left] {$(0,1)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2, 5) (-1, 3) (1, -1) (2, -3)};
                  \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,1) (1,1)} node[pos=0.5,above] {$1$};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(1,1) (1,-1)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$2$};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(1,-1) (2,-1) (2,-3)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,1) (-1,1) (-1,3)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-1,3) (-2,3) (-2,5)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <figure>
          <caption>Graphing <m>y=-2x+1</m> by slope triangles</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              This is a graph of the line y=-2x+1. The following points on the line are plotted:
              (-2,5),(-1,3),( 0,1),(1,-1),(2,-3). There are a few slope triangles. One starts at
              (-2,5), passes (-1,5), and ends at (-1,3). One    starts at (-1,3), passes (0,3),
              and ends at (0,1). One starts at (0,1), passes (1,1), and ends at (1,-1). One starts
              at (1,-1), passes (2,-1), and ends at (2,-3).
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="summary-negative-slope-intercept">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-3,
                    xmax=3,
                    ymin=-6,
                    ymax=6,
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = -2.5:3]{-2*x+1} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {$y=-2x+1$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2, 5) (-1, 3) (0, 1) (1, -1) (2, -3)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,1) (1,1) (1,-1)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(1,-1) (2,-1) (2,-3)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,1) (-1,1) (-1,3)};
                  \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-1,3) (-2,3) (-2,5)};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        Compared to the table method, the slope triangle method:
        <ul>
          <li>is more sophisticated;</li>
          <li>doesn't take the time and space to make a table;</li>
          <li>doesn't involve lots of calculations where you might make a human error;</li>
          <li>shows slope triangles, which reinforces the meaning of slope.</li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </example>
    <example>
      <title>Using intercepts</title>
      <p>
        If we use <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-intercepts to plot <m>y=-2x+1</m>, we have to find those
        intercepts first. For our current line, it is apparent that the <m>y</m>-intercept is at
        <m>(0,1)</m>. But where is the <m>x</m>-intercept?
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          Set <m>y=0</m>.
          <md>
            <mrow>y\amp=-2x+1</mrow>
            <mrow>\substitute{0}\amp=-2x+1</mrow>
            <mrow>0\subtractright{1}\amp=-2x</mrow>
            <mrow>-1\amp=-2x</mrow>
            <mrow>\divideunder{-1}{-2}\amp=x</mrow>
            <mrow>\frac{1}{2}\amp=x</mrow>
          </md>
          So the <m>x</m>-intercept is at <m>\left(\frac{1}{2},0\right)</m>. Plotting both
          intercepts, we can connect the dots with a straight line.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption>Using slope triangles</caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="summary-graph-using-slope-triangles">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-3,
                    xmax=3,
                    ymin=-6,
                    ymax=6,
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = -2.5:3]{-2*x+1} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {$y=-2x+1$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 1)} node[below left] {$(0,1)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0.5, 0)} node[above right] {$\left(\frac{1}{2},0\right)$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        This worked, but here are some observations about why this method is not the greatest.
        <ul>
          <li>
            Algebra was required to solve for at least one of the intercepts.
          </li>
          <li>
            We had to plot a point with a fraction in its coordinates.
          </li>
          <li>
            We only plotted two points and they turned out to be very close to each other. So if
            there is even a small inaccuracy in where we marked the points or how we use a straight
            edge, it could result in a line that is significantly off.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </example>
    <note>
      <p>
        When a line is presented in
        <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref> and
        <m>b</m> is an integer, our opinion is that the slope triangle method is the best choice for
        making its graph.
      </p>
    </note>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Graphing Lines in Point-Slope Form</title>
    <p>
      When we graph a line in
      <xref ref="equation-point-slope-form" text="custom">point-slope form</xref> like
      <m>y=\frac{2}{3}(x+1)+3</m>, the slope triangle method is the obvious choice. We can see a
      point on the line, <m>(-1,3)</m>, and the slope is apparent: <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>. Here is the
      graph:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Graphing <m>y=\frac{2}{3}(x+1)+3</m> using slope triangles</caption>
      <image width="47%">
        <shortdescription>
          This is a graph of the line y-3=2/3(x+1). The following points on the line are plotted:
          (-4,1),(-1,3),(2,5). There are two slope triangles. One starts at (-4,1), passes (-1,1),
          and ends at (-1,3). One starts at (-1,3), passes (2,3), and ends at (2,5).
        </shortdescription>
        <latex-image label="summary-graph-point-slope">
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[
                xmin=-5,
                xmax=3,
                width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                ymin=-1,
                ymax=6
              ]
              \addplot+[domain = -5:3]{2/3*(x+1)+3} node[pos=0.25,sloped,below] {$y=\frac{2}{3}(x+1)+3$};
              \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-4, 1) (2, 5)};
              \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1, 3)} node[above left] {$(-1,3)$};
              \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-1,3) (-4,3) (-4,1)};
              \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(-1,3) (2,3)} node[pos=0.5,above] {$3$};
              \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(2,3) (2,5)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$2$};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Other graphing methods would take more work and miss the purpose of
      <xref ref="equation-point-slope-form" text="custom">point-slope form</xref>. To graph a line
      in <xref ref="equation-point-slope-form" text="custom">point-slope form</xref>, we
      recommend always using slope triangles.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Graphing Lines in Standard Form</title>
    <p>
      The line <m>3x+4y=12</m> is in
      <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="custom">standard form</xref>. How should we graph it?
      We'll review methods we learned and compare them.
    </p>

    <example>
      <title>Building a Table of <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-values</title>
      <p>
        To make a table, we could substitute <m>x</m> for various numbers and use algebra to find
        the corresponding <m>y</m>-values. Let's start with <m>x=-2</m>, planning to move on to
        <m>x=-1,0,1,2</m>.
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>3x+4y\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>3(\substitute{-2})+4y\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>-6+4y\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>4y\amp=12\addright{6}</mrow>
            <mrow>4y\amp=18</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{18}{4}=\frac{9}{2}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          The first point we found is <m>\left(-2,\frac{9}{2}\right)</m>. This has been a lot of
          calculation, and we ended up with a fraction we will have to plot. <em>And</em> we have to
          repeat this process a few more times to get more points for the table. The table method is
          generally not a preferred way to graph a line in
          <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="custom">standard form</xref>. So let's look at
          other options.
        </p>
      </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>Using intercepts</title>
      <p>
        Next, we'll try graphing <m>3x+4y=12</m> using intercepts. We set up a small table to record
        the two intercepts:
      </p>
      <sidebyside>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="left"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell/>
            <cell><m>x</m>-value</cell>
            <cell><m>y</m>-value</cell>
            <cell>Intercept</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>x</m>-intercept</cell>
            <cell/>
            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell/>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>y</m>-intercept</cell>
            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell/>
            <cell/>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </sidebyside>

      <sidebyside valign="top" widths="47% 47%">
        <p>
          We have to calculate the line's <m>x</m>-intercept by substituting <m>y=0</m> into the equation:
          <md>
            <mrow>3x+4y\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>3x+4(\substitute{0})\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>3x\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=\divideunder{12}{3}</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=4</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          And similarly for the <m>y</m>-intercept:
          <md>
            <mrow>3x+4y\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>3(\substitute{0})+4y\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>4y\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{12}{4}</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=3</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        So the line's <m>x</m>-intercept is at <m>(4,0)</m> and its <m>y</m>-intercept is at
        <m>(0,3)</m>. Now we can complete the table and then graph the line:
      </p>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <figure>
          <caption>Intercepts of <m>3x+4y=12</m></caption>
          <tabular>
            <col halign="left"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <col halign="center"/>
            <row bottom="medium">
              <cell/>
              <cell><m>x</m>-value</cell>
              <cell><m>y</m>-value</cell>
              <cell>Intercepts</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>x</m>-intercept</cell>
              <cell><m>4</m></cell>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(4,0)</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell><m>y</m>-intercept</cell>
              <cell><m>0</m></cell>
              <cell><m>3</m></cell>
              <cell><m>(0,3)</m></cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <caption>Graph of <m>3x+4y=12</m></caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
              This is a grid with the graph of line 3x+4y=12. The following points are plotted:
              (0,3), (4,0).
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="summary-graph-standard-form">
              \begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[
                    xmin=-1,
                    xmax=6,
                    ymin=-1,
                    ymax=4,
                    width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ]
                  \addplot+[domain = -1:5.3333]{-3/4*x+3} node[pos=0.5,above,sloped] {$3x+4y=12$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 3)} node[color=firstcolor, above right] {$(0,3)$};
                  \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4, 0)} node[color=firstcolor, above right] {$(4,0)$};
                \end{axis}
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </sidebyside>
    </example>

    <example>
      <title>With Slope Triangles</title>
      <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
        <p>
          We can always rearrange <m>3x+4y=12</m> into
          <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>, and
          then graph it with the slope triangle method:
        </p>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>3x+4y\amp=12</mrow>
            <mrow>4y\amp=12\subtractright{3x}</mrow>
            <mrow>4y\amp=-3x+12</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{-3x+12}{4}</mrow>
            <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{3}{4}x+3</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
        With the <m>y</m>-intercept at <m>(0,3)</m> and slope <m>-\frac{3}{4}</m>, we can graph the
        line using slope triangles:
      </p>

      <figure>
        <caption>Graphing <m>3x+4y=12</m> using slope triangles</caption>
        <image width="47%">
          <shortdescription>
            This is a graph of the line 3x+4y=12. The following points on the line are plotted:
            (-4,6),(0,3),(4,0). There  are  two slope triangles. One starts at (-4,6), passes (0,6),
            and ends at (0,3). One starts at (0,3), passes (4,3), and  ends at   (4,0).
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="summary-graph-standard-form-using-intercepts">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xmin=-5,
                  xmax=5,
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                  ymin=-2,
                  ymax=7
                ]
                \addplot+[domain = -5:5]{-3/4*x+3} node[pos=0.25,sloped,above] {$3x+4y=12$};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-4, 6) (4, 0)};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,3)} node[above right] {$(0,3)$};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,3) (-4,3) (-4,6)};
                \addplot[guideline,-] coordinates {(0,3) (4,3)} node[pos=0.5,above] {$4$};
                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(4,3) (4,0)} node[pos=0.5,right] {$-3$};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Compared with the intercepts method, the slope triangle method takes more time, but it
        works.
      </p>
    </example>

    <p>
      Here are some observations about graphing a line equation that is in
      <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="custom">standard form</xref>:
      <ul>
        <li>
          The intercepts method might be the quickest approach.
        </li>
        <li>
          The intercepts method only tells us two intercepts of the line. When we need to know more
          information, like the line's slope, and get a more accurate graph, we should take the time
          to convert the equation into slope-intercept form.
        </li>
        <li>
          When <m>C=0</m> in a
          <xref ref="equation-standard-form" text="custom">standard form equation</xref> we cannot
          use the intercepts method to plot the line anyway.
        </li>
      </ul>
      So there's not really a clear winner for which method is best. Using intercepts or converting
      to slope-intercept form and using slope triangels might be preferable depending on the
      situation.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Graphing Horizontal and Vertical Lines</title>
    <p>
      We learned in <xref ref="section-geometry-of-lines"/> that equations in the form <m>x=h</m>
      and <m>y=k</m> make vertical and horizontal lines. But perhaps you will one day find yourself
      not remembering which is which. Making a table and plotting points can quickly remind you
      which type of equation makes which type of line. Let's build a table for <m>y=2</m> and
      another one for <m>x=-3</m>:
    </p>

    <sidebyside margins="0%">
      <figure>
        <caption>Table of values for <m>y=2</m></caption>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell><m>x</m>-value</cell>
            <cell><m>y</m>-value</cell>
            <cell>Point</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(0,2)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(1,2)</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </figure>
      <figure>
        <caption>Table of values for <m>x=-3</m></caption>
        <tabular>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <col halign="center"/>
          <row bottom="medium">
            <cell><m>x</m>-value</cell>
            <cell><m>y</m>-value</cell>
            <cell>Point</cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(-3,0)</m></cell>
          </row>
          <row>
            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell><m>(-3,1)</m></cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>
      </figure>
    </sidebyside>
    <p>
      With two points on each line, we can graph them:
    </p>
    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
      <figure>
        <caption>Graphing <m>y=2</m></caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a graph of y=2; the points (0,2) and (1,2) are plotted, and a horizontal line passes
            between them
          </shortdescription>

          <latex-image label="summary-graph-horizontal">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xmin=-4,
                  xmax=4,
                  ymin=-3,
                  ymax=3,
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                ]
                \addplot+[] coordinates {(-4,2) (4,2)} node[pos=0.5,above] {$y=2$};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 2)} node[below left] {$(0,2)$};
                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1, 2)} node[below right] {$(1,2)$};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <figure>
        <caption>Graphing <m>x=-3</m></caption>
        <image>
          <shortdescription>
            a graph of x=-3; the points (-3,0) and (-3,1) are plotted, and a vertical line passes
            between them
          </shortdescription>
          <latex-image label="summary-graph-vertical">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
              \begin{axis}[
                  xmin=-4,
                  xmax=4,
                  ymin=-3,
                  ymax=3,
                  width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                ]
                \addplot+[] coordinates {(-3,-3) (-3,3)} node[pos=0.5,sloped,above] {$x=-3$};
                \addplot[soliddot, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(-3, 0)} node[above right] {$(-3,0)$};
                \addplot[soliddot, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(-3, 1)} node[above right] {$(-3,1)$};
              \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </sidebyside>
  </subsection>
